///Simple string type
///This string type is designed for robustness and ease of reasoning.
///It can only even contain the following whitelisted characters:
///0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyzABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ+-*/=<>,.;:()[]{}`'"!?@#$%^&_|~\
///Plus space ` ` and new line.
///There is no concept of escape as in some other languages, so `\n` is two characters.
///The methods ^ and | can be used to obtain a string including new lines or backticks (`).

/// Relations of parsers and printers.
/// Methods .getInt/.getFloat/.getNum/.getByte below accept exactly the numeric type names
/// accepted by the Fearless syntax, including the allowed `_` as for the Fearless syntax.
/// They *do not* evaluate expressions.
/// Str.escape, Float.str and Float.ieeeStr  instead output Fearless code when there is no literal represing the value.
///
/// Str.getInt:
/// - rejected: `12`.getInt  `+1_`.getInt  `+_1`.getInt
//  - accepted: `+12`.getInt, `+1_000`.getInt  `+0__10`.getInt  `+01__0`.getInt `+1__0`.getInt `+00`.getInt `-00`.getInt `-001`.getInt `+001`.getInt
/// - canonicalization: `+00_12`.getInt.str ==`+12`
///
/// Str.getNat:
/// - rejected: `+12`.getNat  `-1`.getNat  `1_`.getNat  `_1`.getNat    `4_294_967_296`.getNat (range)
/// - accepted: `0`.getNat  `00`.getNat  `0__10`.getNat  `4_294_967_295`.getNat
/// - canonicalization: `000_255`.nat.str ==`255`  and `4_294_967_295`.nat.str==`4294967295`
///
/// Str.getByte:
/// - rejected: `+12`.getByte  `-1`.getByte  `1_`.getByte  `_1`.getByte  `256`.getByte
/// - accepted: `0`.getByte  `00`.getByte  `0__10`.getByte  `255`.getByte  `000_255`.getByte
/// - canonicalization: `000_255`.getByte.str==`255`
///
/// Str.getNum:
/// - rejected: `12`.getNum  `+12`.getNum  `+1/`.getNum  `+1./2`.getNum  `+1/_2`.getNum  `+1/0`.getNum  `+1.0/0.0`.getNum
/// - accepted: `+12/1`.getNum  `-00_12/000_3`.getNum  `+12.4/3.2`.getNum  `+0/1`.getNum  `-0/1`.getNum
/// - canonicalization: `+12.4/3.2`.getNum!.str==`+31/8`  `+12/2`.getNum!.str==`+6/1`
///
/// Str.getFloat (IEEE 754 binary 64):
/// - rejected (syntax): `1.0`.getFloat  `+1`.getFloat  `+1.`.getFloat  `+.1`.getFloat  `+1e0`.getFloat
/// - rejected (value): `+NaN`.getFloat  `+Infinity`.getFloat  `-Infinity`.getFloat  `+0.1`.getFloat
/// - Float value 0.1 (and many others) do not exist; so it is rejected.
/// - accepted: `+0.5`.getFloat  `+1.25`.getFloat  `+01__0.00__1`.getFloat  `+1.0e-3`.getFloat
/// - canonicalization: `-0.0`.getFloat.str==`+0.0`
///
/// Str.ieeeFloat:
/// - rejected: `duck`.ieeeFloat
/// - accepted: `NaN`.ieeeFloat  `Infinity`.ieeeFloat  `-Infinity`.ieeeFloat  `-0.0`.ieeeFloat  `+0.0`.ieeeFloat  `1e0`.ieeeFloat
/// - canonicalization: `1e0`.ieeeFloat!.ieeeStr==`1.0`  and `+0.0`.ieeeFloat!.ieeeStr==`0.0`  (NaN payload not preserved)
/// - roundtrip (value): f.ieeeStr.ieeeFloat! == f
///   The roundtrip also preserves the sign of zero but not the NaN payload
///   `0.1`.ieeeFloat!.ieeeStr == `0.1` BUT there is no Float representing 0.1 
///   .ieeeFloat + .ieeeStr implement shortest string that round-trips under round-to-nearest ties-to-even
///   That is, `0.1`.ieeeFloat!.ieeeStr lies to you twice, once when it creates the float, and a secon time when
///   it choses to print a near value that has a compact representation instead of the actual content of the float
///   Another example: `0.100000000000000005`.ieeeFloat!.ieeeStr == `0.1`
///   But, `0.100000000000000005` is closer to the actual representable Float value. That is,
///   `+0.1`.ieeeFloat!.getNum!.inRange(+0.100000000000000005/1, +2/1) holds
///   `+0.1`.ieeeFloat!.getNum!.inRange(+0.1/1, +0.100000000000000005/1) does not hold
Str: Sealed,DataType[Str,Str],JoinStr[Str],_AssertImmEmpty,_AssertImmSize {
  .close->::; .close->this;         /// fixpoint type closed
  +(x: read ToStr): Str;            /// string concatenation; throws on result size > maxInt
  |(x: read ToStr): Str;            /// like + but inserts a newline between the two strings
  ^(x: read ToStr): Str;           /// like + but inserts a double quote between the two strings

  | : Str;                          /// appends a newline
  ^ : Str;                         /// appends a double quote
  .isEmpty: Bool;                   /// true iff size == 0
  .size: Nat;                       /// the amount of characters in this string
  .escape: Str;                     /// returns a string representing valid Fearless code which yields this string when evaluated (may use ^ and |, not necessarily a single literal)
  .indexOf(Str): Opt[Nat];          /// index of the first occourence of the parameter. Returns 0 if the parameter is ``
  .sub(from: Nat, to: Nat): Str;    /// substring [from,to); throws on from/to out of the string boundaries or from > to
  .replaceSimultaneous(rules: List[Str]): Str; /// takes a list of pairs and performs simultaneous replacement; throws on empty keys, duplicated keys, odd sized lists, keys with prefixes
  .replaceSimultaneousOrdered(rules: List[Str]): Str; /// takes a list of pairs and performs simultaneous replacement where the first matching rule wins; throws on empty keys, duplicated keys, odd sized lists
  .ieeeFloat: Opt[Float];           /// parse IEEE-754 string; accepts Float.ieeeStr output; .empty on invalid (returns the rounded Float value (ties-to-even), preserving NaN/Inf and signed zero. Float.ieeeStr.ieeeFloat produces the same Float modulo NaN payload; but Str.ieeeFloat.ieeeStr may not produce the same string due to canonicalization+rounding)
  .getFloat: Opt[Float];          /// parse a string representing a valid Fearless Float; .empty on invalid (this includes NaN and +/-Inf since not syntactically valid Float, and values that would round)

  .getInt: Opt[Int];              /// parse a string representing a valid Fearless Int; .empty on invalid (this includes out of range)
  .getNum: Opt[Num];              /// parse a string representing a valid Fearless Num; .empty on invalid (this includes denominator == 0)
  .getNat: Opt[Nat];              /// parse a string representing a valid Fearless Nat; .empty on invalid (this includes out of range)
  .getByte: Opt[Byte];            /// parse a string representing a valid Fearless Nat in the range [0,255]; .empty on invalid (this includes out of range)
  .startsWith(Str): Bool;            /// this string starts with the other string
  .lower: Str;                      /// this string but all lowercase
  .upper: Str;                      /// this string but all uppercase
  .u : UStr;                        /// this string, but as a Unicode string
  .u(values: Str) : UStr;           /// equivalent to this.u.u values
  .norm: Norm[Str];
  }

OrderByCaseInsensitive: OrderBy[Str] { s0,s1,m -> s0.imm.lower <=> (s1.imm.lower, m) }
